[1] Pennsylvania - raccoon, canines, human exposure
Date: 20 Feb 2016
Source: NC News online [edited]
http://www.ncnewsonline.com/news/rabies-case-identified-in-hickory-township/article_f4e7f32c-d749-11e5-91d1-47b04300c201.html


A case of rabies has been confirmed in Hickory Township.

Dr. Erin Moore, a veterinarian with the Pennsylvania Department of Agriculture in Greensbsurg, said 2 humans and a dog were exposed last month [February 2016] to a raccoon that tested positive for rabies. The raccoon's diagnosis was confirmed by the Pennsylvania Department of Agriculture Veterinary Laboratory in Harrisburg.

The humans, she said, will receive preventative rabies treatment. The dog, overdue for a rabies vaccine, received a booster and will be quarantined for 180 days at the owners' Harlansburg Road home.

Moore said the dog was let out by its owners the night of 12 Jan 2016. While outside, the owners heard a commotion and saw the dog fighting with a raccoon.

"I want people to be aware that a rabid raccoon has been identified in the area," she said. "I don't want to frighten people, but they should be aware a case of rabies has been confirmed. They should not approach wild animals, and should ensure their pets' rabies vaccines are current. This is important if their pets go outside and might encounter wild animals."

Under Pennsylvania law, all dogs and non-feral cats aged 3 months and older are to be vaccinated against rabies. Booster vaccinations should be administered periodically to maintain lifelong immunity. Failure to comply with this law may result in a fine of up to USD 300.

