[2] Pennsylvania - feline, human exposure
Date: 25 Feb 2016
Source: Rocket Courrier [edited]
http://www.rocket-courier.com/news/2016-02-25/Front_Page/Rabid_Cat_Bites_Person_in_Wilmot_Township.html


For the 2nd time since September 2015, an individual has been bitten by a feral cat that later tested positive for rabies in the Quicks Bend area of Wilmot Township along Dietz Road.

The PA Department of Agriculture (PDA) issued a press release today, 25 Feb 2016, stating that an individual was petting a feral cat at that location and was bitten. According to PDA Communications Specialist Will Nichols, the incident occurred on 19 Fri Feb 2016.

The cat was later submitted to the PA Veterinary Laboratory in Harrisburg where it tested positive for rabies. The person, unidentified by the PDA, received post exposure rabies prophylaxis.

Nichols said it is unknown whether other feral cats or wild animals in the area were exposed to the infected animal. Residents are urged to avoid contact with all wild animals, especially cats.

"Folks need to be vigilant of feral cats and wild animals that are acting strangely," said Nichols. "The goal of these alerts is to let people know rabies cases have been found in their area and that others in the feral cat population could be infected."

On 9 Sep 2015, a Wilmot Township woman and her daughter were also bitten by a rabid feral cat along Dietz Road [This seems like an old incident to bring up, but I supposed it goes to location. - Mod.TG].

The feral cat ran under a pickup truck parked nearby, and when the woman attempted to shoo it away, it attacked her. The cat then attacked the woman's daughter, who had come to the mother's aid, and bit her [the daughter] as well, but the daughter managed to punch the cat and knock it unconscious. A few minutes later the woman's husband came home and killed the cat. It was later taken to a lab for testing, where it was discovered the cat was rabid.

"People bitten by an animal should seek immediate medical attention and try to have that animal checked for rabies," said Nichols. "Rabies is actually transmitted through the saliva, so it doesn't necessarily have to be a bite."

Nichols said the investigating field team did not establish a connection between the 2 incidents.

State law requires all dogs and non-feral cats 3 months of age and older to be vaccinated against rabies. Booster vaccinations must be administered periodically to maintain lifelong immunity. Failure to comply with the law may result in a fine of up to USD 300.

