[3] Florida - feline, human exposure
Date: 19 Feb 2016
Source: WFLA.com [edited]
http://wfla.com/2016/02/19/rabid-cat-attacks-citrus-park-man-5-stray-cats-euthanized/


If you live in Citrus Park and your cat is missing, you might want to check with the county. Hillsborough County's Pet Resources recently trapped and euthanized 5 strays in the area after a rabid cat attacked and killed 2 other cats, then attacked a man in Citrus Park on Saturday [13 Feb 2016?].

The county euthanized the stray cats in order to find out whether rabies had spread to other animals.

Rabies notifications went out earlier this week to schools, businesses and homes near the intersection of Ehrlich and Del Valle roads in Citrus Park after the stray cat that attacked tested positive for rabies.

"When animals have ferocious rabies, they pretty well attack anything that moves," said Brian Miller, an Environmental Administrator with Florida's Department of Health in Hillsborough County. [Generally rabies is divided into 2 categories: furious and dumb. Ferocious rabies is not a rabies category, however descriptive it may be. Generally, furious rabies is where the animal is furious or ferocious, attacking frequently, and the manner of the animal may be quite unlike the normal personality of the animal. - Mod.TG]

As for the euthanized cats, the state and county are waiting for results to see whether rabies has spread.

According to the county, this is the same area where, a couple of years ago, they had problems with rabid raccoons.

[Byline: Steve Andrews]

