[7] New Jersey - feline, human exposure
Date: 24 Mar 2016
Source: North Jersey.com [edited]
http://www.northjersey.com/news/four-saddle-river-residents-advised-to-get-treatment-after-stray-cat-found-to-have-rabies-1.1532985


Four Saddle River residents were advised to begin treatment for rabies after a stray cat that they had been exposed to was found to have the potentially deadly disease, authorities said Thursday [24 Mar 2016]. [Rabies is a deadly disease for humans without treatment. Rabies is deadly to animals. The word potentially is misleading. - Mod.TG]

Saddle River Police Capt. Jason Cosgriff said in a statement that the New Jersey Department of Health confirmed Wednesday [23 Mar 2016] the cat had tested positive for rabies, and 4 people had been identified as having had contact with the animal before its death. The cat did not have a current rabies vaccination, Cosgriff said.

Police said further information was not immediately available about the nature of the contacts the 4 people had with the cat or the manner in which the cat died, nor was any information provided concerning when and where in Saddle River the contacts had occurred.

Cosgriff cautioned residents to be certain that all pets are vaccinated for rabies annually but noted that animals are not considered immunized until 28 days after receiving the vaccine for the 1st time. Newly vaccinated animals and animals that can't be vaccinated because they are less than 3 months old should not be allowed outdoors alone, he said.

The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention says that the initial symptoms of rabies in human beings can include fever, headache and general weakness or discomfort.

But as the disease progresses, signs in animals [sic; he means humans] may include insomnia, anxiety, confusion, slight or partial paralysis, excitation, hallucinations, agitation, increased salivation, difficulty swallowing and fear of water. Death usually occurs within days of the onset of these symptoms, according to the CDC.

[Byline: Jim Norman]

