[Very few of these articles mention the need to have your pets vaccinated as a protective layer between yourself and rabies infected animals. Protection of your pet also saves the heartache of having your own pet euthanized when exposed to a rabid animal.

There are 2 forms of rabies: furious and paralytic (sometimes referred to as dumb). The signs described herein are characteristic of the different forms, but an individual rabid animal would not necessarily show all the clinical signs.

Furious rabies
- The animal displays signs of extreme restlessness and aggression.
- It attacks objects, other animals, and even its own limbs.
- Fits of furious rabies generally alternate with periods of withdrawal.

Paralytic (dumb) rabies
- The animal may become withdrawn and seek seclusion.
- It may no longer be afraid of humans.
- A generally nocturnal animal may become active during the day.
- Signs of paralysis: Head and neck paralysis may result in an abnormal facial expression, excessive salivation, slackness of the head and jaw, and making strange sounds. Body paralysis normally begins with the hind legs and spreads to the rest of the body.

Species-specific signs
The signs described above are common to all species. Nevertheless, more specific signs can be observed in certain species of domestic animals infected with the rabies virus.

Cattle rarely develop furious rabies but, when they do, they may attack humans. A characteristic sign of rabies in cattle is abnormal bellowing, which may be continuous or intermittent, and lasts until the animal dies. In dairy cows infected with rabies, milk production will drop off suddenly. The bellowing is very distinctive -- for lack of a better descriptive term -- something from a horror movie.

Horses may show signs of distress and agitation. These signs, accompanied by rolling, give the appearance of colic. Rabid horses can be prone to aggression and self-mutilation. Rabid horses have attacked people.

Rabid pigs display rapid chewing, lack of coordination, and repetitive headshaking.

Sheep infected with the rabies virus have a hoarse bleat, tend to lick objects, and become aggressive.

There are no treatments for wild or domestic animals exposed to the rabies virus. Death generally occurs within 10 days of the onset of clinical signs.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from: http://www.rage.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?formes-de-rage-en. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4122167,106.]
